<h2 id="sixxsfeaturedinlinuxjournalmay-0502" class="entry-title">SixXS featured in Linux Journal (May 2013 / #229)</h2>
<abbr class="updated" title="2013-02-05T13:42:00-00:00">Thursday, May 2nd, 2013</abbr></header>
<div class="vcard" style="visibility: hidden">
	<a class="url fn" href="http://www.sixxs.net/">SixXS</a>
</div>
<div class="entry-content">
<div class="newslinksbox">
<a href="http://www.linuxjournal.com/content/may-2013-issue-linux-journal-raspberry-pi" class="nolines"><img src="/s/news.gif" alt="" /></a>
<div class="newslinks">
<a href="http://www.linuxjournal.com/content/may-2013-issue-linux-journal-raspberry-pi" title="Link to related material">related link</a><br />
<a href="/news/2013/#sixxsfeaturedinlinuxjournalmay-0502" title="Permanent link to this article, useful for bookmarking" rel="bookmark">permlink</a>
</div>
</div>
<p>
The <a href="http://www.linuxjournal.com/content/may-2013-issue-linux-journal-raspberry-pi">May 2013 (Issue 229)</a> version of <a href="http://www.linuxjournal.com/">Linux Journal</a> has several articles about the extremely versatile <a href="http://www.raspberrypi.org">Raspberry Pi</a>.
</p>
<p>
Amongst other good articles, on the cover the text "Use an RPi as a Low-Cost IPv6 Route and Tunnel Endpoint" is noted. The related article is on page 78 and is titled "Autoconfiguring an IPv6 Access Point with SixXS and a Raspberry Pi" written by Igor Partola
It details how one can use SixXS to set up IPv6 connectivity when your ISP does not already support IPv6 using a Pi as the tunnel endpoint and even use it for roaming around taking your IPv6 with you to other networks without having a worry of the tunnel breaking due to the changing address or NAT.
</p>
<p>
A copy of this edition of the Linux Journal can be retrieved from the <a href="ftp://ftp.linuxjournal.com/pdf/dlj229.pdf">Linux Journal FTP server</a>.
</p>

</div>
</article>
